1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,040
A few years ago, I met a student named Alex.

2
00:00:03,040 --> 00:00:06,340
Alex had studied English for almost seven years.

3
00:00:06,460 --> 00:00:07,667
He knew grammar rules.

4
00:00:07,768 --> 00:00:09,700
He knew hundreds of words.

5
00:00:09,820 --> 00:00:14,020
But when someone spoke to him in English, his heart started beating faster.

6
00:00:14,315 --> 00:00:19,155
His mind went blank, and the words he knew simply disappeared.

7
00:00:19,115 --> 00:00:22,514
One day, Alex told me something I will never forget.

8
00:00:22,715 --> 00:00:26,675
He said, I understand English, but English doesn't come out of me.

9
00:00:26,979 --> 00:00:31,580
And that sentence explains the problem of millions of English learners around the world.

10
00:00:31,540 --> 00:00:34,920
Alex believed he was bad at English, but he wasn't.

11
00:00:34,920 --> 00:00:37,500
He was just learning it the wrong way.

12
00:00:37,540 --> 00:00:39,260
I told Alex something simple.

13
00:00:39,425 --> 00:00:43,705
Stop preparing to speak English and start speaking English.

14
00:00:43,745 --> 00:00:45,045
At first he laughed.

15
00:00:45,045 --> 00:00:47,284
He said, but I will make mistakes.

16
00:00:47,284 --> 00:00:52,025
I smiled and said, yes, and that's exactly how fluency is built.

17
00:00:52,300 --> 00:00:55,220
So, Alex changed one small habit.

18
00:00:55,260 --> 00:00:58,980
Every morning, he listened to ten minutes of real English.

19
00:00:58,940 --> 00:01:02,980
Not lessons, not grammar, just real conversations.

20
00:01:03,580 --> 00:01:06,179
At night, he spoke English for ten minutes.

21
00:01:06,465 --> 00:01:12,744
Sometimes to himself, sometimes into his phone, sometimes in broken sentences.

22
00:01:13,265 --> 00:01:14,505
But he spoke.

23
00:01:14,945 --> 00:01:17,225
In the beginning, it was uncomfortable.

24
00:01:17,265 --> 00:01:18,564
He felt stupid.

25
00:01:18,564 --> 00:01:20,905
He felt slow, but he didn't stop.

26
00:01:21,150 --> 00:01:26,309
Instead of memorizing long word lists, Alex started learning phrases.

27
00:01:26,830 --> 00:01:30,950
Not important, but it's important to.

28
00:01:31,230 --> 00:01:35,429
Not decision, but I need to make a decision.

29
00:01:36,355 --> 00:01:40,875
Slowly, English stopped being a puzzle and started becoming a tool.

30
00:01:40,915 --> 00:01:43,995
Something interesting happened after a few weeks.

31
00:01:44,035 --> 00:01:47,595
Alex noticed he was thinking in English without trying.

32
00:01:47,795 --> 00:01:51,389
When he was tired, he thought, I need a break.

33
00:01:51,990 --> 00:01:55,389
When he was busy, he thought, I'll do this later.

34
00:01:55,910 --> 00:01:58,749
English was no longer something he translated.

35
00:01:58,790 --> 00:02:00,669
It was something he used.

36
00:02:00,630 --> 00:02:03,389
Three months later, Alex spoke again.

37
00:02:03,430 --> 00:02:04,990
His grammar wasn't perfect.

38
00:02:05,305 --> 00:02:07,184
His accent wasn't perfect.

39
00:02:07,465 --> 00:02:09,345
But his confidence was new.

40
00:02:09,705 --> 00:02:11,585
He wasn't afraid anymore.

41
00:02:11,785 --> 00:02:16,225
And that fear, not grammar, was the real enemy all along.

42
00:02:16,185 --> 00:02:20,225
In 2026, the fastest English learners are not the smartest.

43
00:02:20,660 --> 00:02:22,120
They are the bravest.

44
00:02:22,120 --> 00:02:24,220
They speak before they feel ready.

45
00:02:24,340 --> 00:02:26,460
They make mistakes without shame.

46
00:02:26,580 --> 00:02:30,059
They practice daily even when progress feels slow.

47
00:02:30,180 --> 00:02:32,940
If Alex can do it, so can you.

48
00:02:33,060 --> 00:02:34,620
You don't need more rules.

49
00:02:35,025 --> 00:02:36,825
You don't need more books.

50
00:02:37,025 --> 00:02:41,065
You need courage, consistency, and daily action.

51
00:02:41,185 --> 00:02:42,745
Ten minutes of listening.

52
00:02:42,705 --> 00:02:44,265
Ten minutes of speaking.

53
00:02:44,225 --> 00:02:45,605
Every single day.

54
00:02:45,605 --> 00:02:47,945
English fluency is not a miracle.

55
00:02:47,905 --> 00:02:51,840
It is a story you write yourself, one sentence at a time.

56
00:02:51,880 --> 00:02:54,640
And the best time to start that story is today.

57
00:02:56,040 --> 00:02:57,840
I have a question for you.

58
00:02:57,960 --> 00:03:02,799
If you think your English is good, I want you to try this and write your answer in the comments.

59
00:03:03,055 --> 00:03:06,215
Which sentence sounds the most natural in everyday English?

60
00:03:06,175 --> 00:03:08,675
A, that's the reason why I left early.

61
00:03:08,675 --> 00:03:10,995
B, that's the reason I left early.

62
00:03:10,995 --> 00:03:13,155
C, that's why I left early.

63
00:03:13,155 --> 00:03:15,255
D, that's the reason because I left early.

64
00:03:15,436 --> 00:03:18,576
Take a few seconds to think and write your answer in the comments.

65
00:03:18,576 --> 00:03:19,536
Go ahead.

66
00:03:19,536 --> 00:03:20,176
I'll wait.
